        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>785</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0040</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0040.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Closed linear span">Closed linear span</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The closed linear span of a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of a normed vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is the closure of the linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[span(S)]]></fr:tex>, is the set of all finite linear combinations of elements in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[span(S) = \{\sum _{i=1}^n a_i v_i : n \in  \mathbb {N}, a_i \in  \mathbb {K}, v_i \in  S\}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>The closure of a set in a normed space is the set together with all its limit points. So the closed linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, often denoted by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {span(S)}]]></fr:tex>, consists of all vectors that can be approximated arbitrarily well by finite linear combinations of elements in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In the context of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0053.xml" addr="FA-0053" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal set</fr:link>, then a vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is in the closed linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> if and only if:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = \sum _i \langle  v, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where the sum converges in the norm.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>787</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0037</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0037.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The Kronecker delta, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>, is a function of two variables, usually integers, that is 1 if the variables are equal and 0 otherwise. Formally:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij} =  \begin {cases}  1 & \text {if } i = j \\ 0 & \text {if } i \neq  j \end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>The Kronecker delta is widely used in many areas of mathematics, including linear algebra, tensor calculus, and functional analysis. In the context of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0053.xml" addr="FA-0053" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal sets</fr:link> or bases in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, the inner product of basis elements is given by the Kronecker delta:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = \delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>This expresses the fact that the basis elements are orthogonal to each other (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \neq  j]]></fr:tex>) and have unit norm (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_i \rangle  = 1]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>789</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0045</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0045.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal Basis">Orthonormal Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An orthonormal basis for a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0053.xml" addr="FA-0053" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal set</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> of vectors in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> such that the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0040.xml" addr="FA-0040" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is the entire space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, an orthonormal basis is an orthonormal set that is also <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> in the sense that any vector in the Hilbert space can be approximated arbitrarily well by finite linear combinations of the basis elements.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal basis of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> if and only if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[x = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Important properties include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Every Hilbert space has an orthonormal basis (this requires the <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0054">Axiom of Choice</fr:link> for general Hilbert spaces)</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-0046.xml" addr="FA-0046" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link> holds for orthonormal bases</fr:li>
<fr:li>Any two orthonormal bases of the same Hilbert space have the same cardinality</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
